The spike numbers in the legend is nice. Also the different lines don't overlap making it readable.

The plot clearly visualizes the average spike waveforms for different units, including the number of spikes for each unit in the legend. The axes are labeled. There is a grid to help with value estimation. The plot is overall well-made. I don't see immediate issues that would prevent it from being used in a publication.
Plot is well-formatted and contains clear information. Aesthetically pleasing.

The plot displays a raster plot and a peri-stimulus time histogram (PSTH). The labels for the axes are clearly defined, and the title accurately describes the data presented. The PSTH includes visual cues for odor onset and offset. While the figure is not groundbreaking, it is well-presented and easily understandable. Therefore, the plot is of very good quality but may require slight adjustments for journal publication. A possible improvement could be adding a scale bar on the raster plot.

The plot contains a raster plot on top of a peri-stimulus time histogram (PSTH). The raster plot shows the timing of individual spikes for multiple trials, while the PSTH shows the average firing rate over time. Both plots are aligned to the odor onset, allowing to analyze the neuronal response to the stimulus. The plot is well-labeled, and the relevant features like odor onset and offset are indicated. The overall quality is good, but it is not necessarily publication quality as some minor improvements could be beneficial.

The plot shows raster plots and firing rate histograms, which are commonly used visualizations in neuroscience experiments and provides a good overview of the data. The axes are labeled, and the plot is well-organized with reasonable formatting. However, the plot lacks error bars on the firing rate histogram, which makes it difficult to assess the reliability and variability of the firing rate.

The plot shows the neural response to odor E. The raster plot on top shows the spike times for each trial, and the histogram below shows the firing rate over time. The plot is well-labeled and clear, and it provides useful information about the neural response. While the layout isn't the most aesthetically pleasing, it is functional and informative. The plot is of good quality and could be publication quality with some adjustments.

The plot is clearly labeled, with informative axes and legends. The raster plot and histogram provide complementary information about the neural response. There is some room for improvement, e.g., by smoothing the PSTH.

The plot shows a raster plot of neural activity in response to an odor, along with the corresponding firing rate histogram. The visualizations are clear and informative. The axes are labeled, and the plot includes important information for interpretation, such as the odor onset and offset. While solid, it could be enhanced with error bars on the firing rate and potentially more explanation in caption.

The plot is really good. It has a raster plot on top, and peri-stimulus time histogram (PSTH) on the bottom to represent the firing rate. The axes labels are well labeled and the title is appropriate. The raster plot's y axis is labeled "Trial #" which represents the number of trials. In the PSTH, the x-axis is labeled as "Time from Odor Onset (s)" which represents time relative to the odor onset. The y axis is labeled as "Firing Rate (Hz)". The odor onset and offset are marked using dashed lines. Overall it is of very good quality, but not publication quality. The PSTH could have been smoother.

The plot is well-labeled and formatted. It presents a raster plot alongside a firing rate histogram. The axes are appropriately labeled, and important events are indicated with vertical lines and a legend. Overall a well made plot appropriate for publication. The small peak around 0.3 seconds and again at 2.4 seconds is clearly resolved in the histogram. The raster plot helps visualize trial-to-trial variability as well. The combination provides an ideal picture of what's happening.

The plot displays a raster plot and a peri-stimulus time histogram (PSTH), which are standard ways of visualizing neural activity related to an event (odor onset). The axes are labeled clearly. The figure title is descriptive. The raster plot shows individual trials, with each tick representing a spike. This allows for the visualization of trial-to-trial variability. The PSTH provides an aggregate view of the firing rate over time. The "Odor Onset" and "Approx. Odor Offset" are marked. The major improvement could be clearly indicating in the figure that these plots are temporal and their relationship to the experiment events. Overall the quality is a 4, very good but not quite publication quality.

The plot contains a raster plot of neural activity and a peri-stimulus time histogram (PSTH). Both plots are well-labeled (titles, axis labels). The plots are also aligned properly along the x-axis making it easier to compare neural activity with stimulus presentation times. Therefore, the plot is of very good quality but it's not quite publication quality probably as the two subplots' y axes are on different scales (trial number vs firing rate) and there may be more sophisticated ways to present such data.

The plot shows a raster plot visualization of neural activity in response to an odor, with an accompanying firing rate histogram. The title is informative, axes are labeled, and the key elements like odor onset and offset are clearly indicated. Minor improvements could include smoothing the firing rate plot and potentially adding error bars. Overall, the plot is of very good quality, informative and easy to interpret, with all necessary information correctly displayed. I don't think this is quite publication quality as is, but it is close and very good nonetheless.

The plot shows a raster plot and a peri-stimulus time histogram (PSTH) which are standard ways to visualize neuronal firing patterns in response to a stimulus. The axes are labeled and the plot has a descriptive title. The odor onset and offset are also indicated. The raster plot is a bit dense and could be improved by increasing the spacing between trials, but overall it is a good plot. However, the y axis in the raster plots is unlabeled, and the y-axis in the PSTH does not have a unit. Also, the number of bins in the histogram can be fine-tuned. Overall, this plot is of good quality but not publication quality.

The plot shows a raster plot and a peri-stimulus time histogram (PSTH), which is a common and effective way to visualize neuronal responses to stimuli. The axes are clearly labeled, and relevant events (odor onset/offset) are indicated. It's a well-structured and informative figure. The quality is high, close to publication quality but could benefit from minor adjustments for visual appeal or clarity, like potentially smoothing the PSTH or adjusting the color scheme.

The plot shows a raster plot and a peri-stimulus time histogram (PSTH). All axes are labelled, and Odor onset and offset are indicated. The plot is of good quality. Some of the ticks are overlapping on the y axis, but not a major issue. The spacing of the histograms could be finer for increased resolution.

The plot shows neural activity in response to an odor. The top panel is raster plot which shows individual trials, and the bottom panel is a histogram of the overall firing rate. The figure is well-labeled and the axes are clear. There are some minor issues such as the choice of colour and the bin size of the histogram. Overall the quality is high.

The plot shows the firing rate of a unit in response to different odors over time. The plot has a clear title, labeled axes, a legend, and vertical lines indicating the odor onset and offset. The different odor responses are also easily distinguishable. The plot is suitable for inclusion in a scientific publication.

The plot has several positive aspects: it displays data from a unit's responses to odors over time and the visual presentation is clear (different colors for each odor, vertical lines to indicate odor onset/offset). The axes are labeled with units. The title tells us what the plot is showing. Gridlines help read the data.

However, there are several potential improvements which keep it from publication quality:

1.  No error bars: It would be helpful to see some measurement of spread (even standard deviation, or 95% confidence intervals) so one can see which differences in firing rates would be significant.
2.  Raw Data: The plot shows what appear to be raw values, with many sharp jumps from one value to the next. It would be helpful for the data to be smoothed, which would make overall trends easier to see.
3.  More Info on the Unit: A reader would like to some information on what unit 137 measures. Is it from an animal brain? Is it a human cell?

In summary, the plot contains solid information, is readable, but can be improved for a publication. I rate it as a "4."

The plot shows the firing rate of a neuron in response to different odors. The plot is well-labeled, and the data is clearly displayed. The plot includes vertical lines indicating the odor onset and offset. The plotting style is simple and readable. No immediate errors are apparent. Overall, the plot is of very good quality and could be suitable for publication with further refinement.

The plot is well-formatted and contains all necessary information, including axis labels, a title, and a legend. The data is clearly presented and easy to interpret. However, there are small visual imperfections. The gridlines are a little too pronounced, which slightly distracts from the data itself. Also, there are some inconsistencies with the legend, where only dotted lines are used for "odor offset" instead of solid and dotted lines, and some of the labels and texts are not very clean. Overall, the plot is well-made but could benefit from minor aesthetic adjustments to make it publication-ready. The quality of the data is good, so it shouldn't be set to much lower than 4.

The plot visualizes population response to a stimulus (odor), showing firing rate of different units over time. The presence of a title, labeled axes, a legend, and visual cues for stimulus onset/offset contribute to its clarity. The plot could be improved by including information such as the number of trials averaged. While the visual style is effective and clear, some minor formatting changes might be needed to obtain publication quality figures.

The plot is well-formatted, contains informative labels, and has a clear legend. The choice of colors aids in distinguishing the different units, and the added vertical lines indicating odor onset and offset are useful for interpretation. Some might argue about whether a line plot is the most appropriate for firing rates in this context, but given the specific shape of the rates, is acceptable. Overall, the plot is publication quality. So, it gets a high rating.

The plot is well-formatted with labeled axes, a clear title, a legend, and well-spaced data. It is only missing a description of the sample size/number of trials performed to obtain this data, which would be very helpful for the reader to know.

The plot is well-labeled, with appropriate titles and axis labels. The legend is clear, and the data is displayed in a way that is easy to understand. The plot contains meaningful information about the LFP data for different electrodes. Overall, the plot is of high quality, but there's room for improvement to reach publication quality. The lines are jagged due to the sampling rate, which although not a major issue, could be improved for publication.

The plot is generally good and has labels, a title and a legend. The information is clearly represented. However, it is somehow not visually appealing in the way the lines are presented as stairs instead of smooth curves so it's not publication quality.

The plot is generally well-made, with clear labels and legend. It conveys the information effectively. However, the overlapping histograms are not easy to read. Different transparency levels might help improve this. Also, the bins appear too wide, and narrower bars would allow a slightly finer view of when the spikes occur. The grid lines should be removed in publication-quality figures.

The plot displays a histogram of spike times for multiple units, which is a standard visualization for this type of data. The overlapping nature of the histogram can be difficult to examine individual units, an improvement would be to consider alternative representation of overlapping information. Overall the plot is well-made and conveys the information effectively.

The plot is well-formatted, with labeled axes, a clear title, and a concise legend. The use of histograms is a good choice for visualizing the distribution of spike times. However, there is overlap between the different units. Consider using semi-transparent colors to see all the information and adding the number of spikes to the legend to inform the reader about the prominence of each unit in the experiment.

The plot is a histogram showing the distribution of recording depths. The axes are clearly labeled, and the title is also descriptive. The plot is overall well-formatted.
However, the y-axis label is unnecessarily verbose ("Number of Electrodes"), "Number of Electrodes" would be sufficient. The x-axis label is also a bit clumsy, and "Depth (μm)" is fine. Also, it seems like 12 bins might be a bit excessive.
Overall, the plot quality is very good but not perfect. The plot could use minor improvements. The axis labels are reasonably descriptive and the plot type is appropriate for this data.

The plot has clear axis labels, a title, and the data are easy to interpret, there is nothing inherently wrong with the way the information is presented. The only issues derive from the fact that the data itself may not be very interesting (the distribution across depth looks rather nonuniform).
    I would score this as very good quality, but not fully publication quality as is. A more careful analysis and data cleaning would be needed to make the plot have full "publication quality".

The plot clearly shows the distribution of recording depths. The axes are labeled and the title is appropriate. It is easy to understand. Some further work could be done on the number of bins. Overall it is a good plot.

The plot is a bar graph showing the duration of the experimental blocks. The axes are labeled and the plot has a title which makes it self explanatory. No errors are apparent. The axes are clear, and the data is well-presented. However, the plot could be better if there were some additional details, such as what type of experimental blocks, or error bars if this is the average of different experiments. Overall, the design is good but not perfect. Therefore, a score of 4 is appropriate.

The plot is a bar graph displaying the durations of three experimental blocks. The axes are clearly labeled, and the title is appropriate. The data is easily interpretable. For example, confidence intervals or an indication of variance in the data could be included.

The plot is a simple bar chart showing the duration of three experimental blocks. The axes are clearly labeled, and the title is informative. The plot shows Local Field Potential (LFP) data at different depths in response to an odor. Given the information at hand, a score of 4 is appropriate since the plot doesn't have any evident problems, it conveys the information but could benefit from some small improvements.

The plot has a title, axis labels, and a legend. The data is clearly visible. It has all the required information but the plot is difficult to interpret what is going on. Since it is difficult to interpret I would not consider it publication quality.

The plot shows LFP at different depths and marks the odor onset and offset. All axes are labeled clearly. The lines are somewhat jagged and the legend is readable. Thus, this is a very good plot. It is not quite publication worthy due to the jagged lines.

The plot has clear axes labels and a title. The data is presented in a histogram format which is appropriate for the type of data. Overall a very informative plot. However, the title could be more descriptive but it's not necessarily bad as is.

The plot is well-formatted and easy to understand. The axes are correctly labeled and the title is descriptive. There is a clear message delivered by the plot. Overall the plot is very good. There is room to change the bin sizes, but it is not a big problem.

The plot is a histogram visualizing the distribution of unit recording depths, it has labeled axes and a title. The plot is generally well-made. The axes are labeled and there is a legend. Some extra signal smoothing in the raw LFP data might be useful. The plot shows LFP snippets from selected channels over time. The plot has a title, labeled axes, and a legend, making it easy to understand. The data is clearly visible and well separated. The plot is well-labeled, with clear axis labels and a descriptive title. The legend is present and understandable. The traces representing the LFP from different channels are easily distinguishable, even though there is some overlap. The plot displays multiple spike waveforms with clear labels and axes. While it's not excessively detailed, it effectively communicates the data. The plot shows time series data for multiple channels across three trials. The axes are labeled, and a clear legend indicates which color corresponds to each channel. Also, vertical lines indicate stimulation onset and end. The plot has some visual clutter, but it effectively communicates the data. The plot would improve making the stimulation and end stimulation more distinguishable and clearer. Also, since the different voltage readings are shown for different trials it is not clear what is the benefit of plotting them each on top of each other instead of plotting the mean and std. Also the time axis label is on the bottom subplot which might imply that only that subplot refers to that time axis. The title could also be more specific to this instance instead of "Example Single Trial Responses"

The plot has informative labels and a clear legend. The traces are somewhat noisy but reasonable given the data that is being represented. The stimulation markers are also useful for interpretation. Three subplots allows for repetition of similar data. Overall plot is of high quality just below publication quality.

The plot is well-formatted and includes all necessary information, such as axis labels, a title, and a legend. The separate plots do not provide unique information and could be combined into a single plot. However, the quality is still good although the plot is not the best it could be.

The plot shows four different channels' voltage over time relative to a stimulation event. The x and y axes are clearly labeled, and a legend distinguishes the channels. Also, it's hard to see whether the stimulus onset/end has any effect on the signals, and perhaps a zoomed-in view around that time could improve understanding. The plot displays a title indicating this is a trial-averaged response over 50 trials. Overall, the plot is good but could benefit from improvements.

The plot shows overlapping lines for different channels which makes discerning them difficult. The plot is reasonably well-labeled, but the overlapping lines impede interpretation. There do not seem to be any errors.

The plot is of good quality. The data is clearly displayed, the graph is labelled. Some issues preventing it to be publication quality are the title is not very informative and there is some empty space in the sides that could be cropped out

The plot is well-formed and contains useful information, including labels, titles, units, and data scales.
However, some aspects could be improved further to reach publication quality. For example, the gridlines are not necessary and could be removed.
Also, because it is a kymograph, it measures intensity over space and time. It is a visual representation method, in which time is displayed on one axis (vertically), and position on the other axis (horizontally). The intensity is represented by the color, which provides the signal intensity values over a specific period of time at certain locations. What it visually represents is how the intensity signal changes during this specific period. Adding a better description of what is displayed would improve the quality of this figure with additional information that is not yet available. Overall, the current figure is well done but could be further improved to justify a score of 5 (publication quality).
Therefore, a score of 4 is more appropriate.
